comments.body:
Hey [~tvo],

Thanks for putting this together.  A little bit of feedback:

* In the ['Assume a Role' document|https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fattachment%2F26711%2Froles_tasks_assume_role_application.dita.pdf]:
I should have included this in my instructions, but I didn't.  My apologies.  At the very end, we should mention how to release a role.  I think the following statement would cover it:
{quote}
4.  To release the role, use {{euare-releaserole}}:
{code}
# eval `/usr/bin/euare-releaserole --region devops-user01@future`
{code}
{quote}

* In the ['Delegate Access Across Accounts Using Roles' document|https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fattachment%2F26712%2Froles_tasks_cross_acct_api_access.dita.pdf]:
Again, this is my fault.  I should have updated this ticket once 4.2 came out.  This way, I could have made it more clear regarding this use case.  I think here, we can mention how this is the programmatic method.  The user can either use a program or use {{euare-assumerole}} to access the role. That being said, in Step 5, could we mention how this is the programmatic method using python boto, and if the user wants to use {{euare-assumerole}}, refer to the 'Assume a Role' use case?  For example:
{quote}
5.  The example below demonstrates how to use a python script leveraging the boto library.  Another way to assume this role would be to use {{euare-assumerole}} using the AccountA/user01 credentials.  For more information regarding assuming a role, please refer to the 'Assume a Role' section.  The script below performs the following actions:
* Access STS to obtain temporary access key ID, secret key, and STS token
* List contents of bucket 'mongodb-snapshots'
....
{quote}

Again thanks for doing this.  I hope this helps.  Please let me know if you have any questions.

[~tvo],

Apologies for this.  I had to reopen this issue because of a security issue that was resolved for 4.2.1 - EUCA-11549.  We need to update the 'Assume a Role' use case.  Information is below:

*Assume a Role*

Between steps 2 and 3, add the following step:
{quote}
3.  Now that the role has been created, follow the [AWS IAM best practice of using groups to assign permission to IAM users|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html#use-groups-for-permissions], and attach an IAM access policy to the group to allow any members to assume the {{devops-ec2-keypair-mgmt-role}} role:
{code}
# euare-groupcreate -g Key-Managers --region devops-admin@future
# euare-groupadduser -u user01 -g Key-Managers --region devops-admin@future
# cat devops-keypair-mgmt-assume-role-policy.json
{
 "Version": "2012-10-17",
 "Statement": [{
 "Effect": "Allow",
 "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
 "Resource": "arn:aws:iam::001827830003:role/devops-ec2-keypair-mgmt-role"
 }]
}
# euare-groupuploadpolicy -p keypair-mgmt-role-perm -f devops-keypair-mgmt-assume-role-policy.json Key-Managers --region devops-admin@future
{code}
{quote}

Again apologies about this.  This was a security fix that was reviewed just yesterday.  Let me know if you need any help with getting it in the docs for 4.2.1.  Thanks ahead of time for working on this.
